. Drawing on fieldwork with gardeners, botanists, migrant workers, refugees, public officials, and nature enthusiasts while charting human and more-than-human worlds, Stoetzer offers a wide-ranging ethnographic portrait of Berlin’s postwar ecologies that reveals emergent futures in the margins of European cities. Brimming with stories that break down divides between environmental perspectives and the study of migration and racial politics, Berlin’s ruderal worlds help us rethink the space of nature and culture and the categories through which we make sense of urban life in inhospitable times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aCity and town lifezGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aHuman ecologyzGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 0aNature and civilizationzGermanyzBerlin. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology)zGermanyzBerlinxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023203?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023203423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023203/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles